Water poured from the roof, making the plants very wet. He looked into the rain, seeming both thoughtful and far away. He had become much thinner, and his clothes hung loose on him. His hair was thinner than before, too. As he kept looking at the rain, he would not meet my eyes. I felt very alone and scared. I could not tell him how much I would miss him because talking about it would make it too real. I gave him a hug, moved my chair closer, and watched the rain with him as evening came.

My father died in December that year, soon after I turned twenty-two. The medical care he received did not stop his pain, but kept him alive longer than doctors thought he would live. I could not understand why he had to suffer more. I questioned why this happened. At night, I stopped praying. I thought if there was a God, He no longer heard me.

I did not want to watch my father die, so I stayed away. I could not see the person who gave me life leave this world. I wanted to remember him as he lived, not as he died. I knew my father better than anyone, and I knew he would not want me to watch him die. I stayed in bed for three days, waiting to hear news.

No one called to tell me when he died.

John Taylor was an early supporter of the ideas that formed the United States. He was mainly a farmer, and his work in farming and brief time in government made him known for speaking strongly about personal freedom and how government should work. His love of farming shaped almost all of his thoughts about government. He tried to protect and support farming because he thought it was the best way of life.

Taylor believed the United States had a special chance to make a perfect system. This was because the new country did not have old rules that would stop people from creating a government run by the people. He strongly believed that people have natural rights. He thought these rights were all connected - if you take away one right, all other rights become weaker. He said the government should not be able to touch these rights. Some people talked about how, in nature, strong and clever but bad people would win. Taylor said this should not happen in a proper society.

Taylor thought that to make a good society, the government must deal with both the good and bad parts of human nature. He had strong beliefs about right and wrong. He said that since people run governments, governments show both good and bad human qualities. He thought good rules were ones that protect what people own, help farming grow, and limit big business. He believed that even if selfish people ran the government, it would still work well if it was built on good rules. Taylor thought people always act for their own good, but this only becomes bad when people hurt others for their own gain. He said we need good government to control people's bad nature, but we must watch the government carefully.

Taylor, like many others who supported the Republican ideas of his time, wanted to follow the Constitution exactly as it was written. He wanted a small federal government that could only do what the Constitution clearly said it could do. He knew that a big federal government would cost too much money and might become too controlling. He also thought the Declaration of Independence was very important because it showed that the United States was made up of separate states working together, not just one big nation.

I looked down at what was in front of me. My mind took in the sight without feeling. Thoughts came and went quickly. It felt like I wasn't really thinking, just seeing.

I once bought a book about drawing after talking to an artist friend. The book was about learning to draw better. I had wanted to learn since I was a child. The book taught many things, including how to look at objects differently. One way was to put a frame around what you want to draw. This makes complex scenes simpler. For example, a bowl of fruit in a kitchen becomes just a bowl on a flat surface.

At that moment, looking down at the bowl, I couldn't think about frames. I could only stand and look. Famous artists like Picasso used blue colors, Monet liked green, and old Italian artists used many colors. If I were an artist, this would be my brown period.

My fingers touched the tool I needed to use. My hand moved through the air as I worked. The water moved smoothly and clearly. Small pieces broke away and disappeared. Moving more quickly the second time, I pushed the handle down again. The brown mass stayed at the bottom of the toilet, not moving.

I stood there holding a mop, wearing a green tie that felt tight. I looked at what someone had left in the bathroom at the store where I worked. After trying to flush several more times, I pulled toilet paper from the wall. I wrapped my hand many times until it was fully covered. Then, I bent down and reached into the toilet, like reaching into an oven for food...

Young people are dying while driving cars. Several things make driving very dangerous for the youngest drivers in America. Studies show that young minds are not ready for the dangers of driving. Not having enough practice is also part of the problem. This lack of experience leads to more deadly crashes, cars turning over, driving too fast, and going off the road.

Young drivers have more problems when they drive with their friends, which they often do. A study in California showed that there is a clear link between how old passengers are and how many crashes happen.

California and other states try to make young drivers safer. They give special permits that only let young people drive at certain times and do not allow other young people to ride with them.

These special permits help, but they are not enough. The facts show that the youngest drivers cannot handle the serious job of driving safely. One expert thinks even age 18 is too young to drive. Studies show that people under age 20 often do dangerous things just for fun. It makes sense to wait until people are older to let them drive. If we keep giving driving permits to young people, more will die. Soon, there will be many more young drivers on the roads.

Making new laws about this would be simple. Schools could still teach driving, but no one under 18 could drive a car. New drivers would still need to practice with teachers and adults for a certain number of hours. The rules should be the same across America because young drivers have problems in every state.

This idea is not new, but it could save many lives.

This paper looks at a brain problem that affects how people understand what they hear. This condition is called Central Auditory Processing Disorder, or CAPD.

First, I will explain what CAPD is. People with CAPD can hear sounds normally, but their brains cannot process these sounds correctly. For example, they may have trouble understanding words when there is other noise in the room. Their ears work fine, but their brains have difficulty making sense of the sounds they hear.

Second, I will describe how doctors find out if someone has CAPD. There are certain signs that may show that a person has this condition. Doctors watch how people listen and respond to different sounds. They also ask questions about how well the person understands speech in different situations.

People with CAPD may have several problems. They might:
- Have trouble knowing where sounds come from
- Find it hard to tell different sounds apart
- Not understand when someone's voice shows feeling, like happiness or anger
- Have difficulty remembering the order of things they hear
- Struggle to understand speech when there is background noise

Finally, I will share ways teachers can help students with CAPD learn better in regular classrooms. This is important because many students with CAPD study in normal school settings.

This condition was first noticed by doctors in the 1950s. Since then, medical experts have worked to better understand how to help people with CAPD. While doctors do not know what causes CAPD, they continue to develop better ways to test for it and help those who have it.

I want to study to become a social worker. My goal is to work for the government helping children who have been hurt by their families. I also want to help families who are having problems. I believe I can bring important things to this work: helping others, showing respect, doing what is right, and always trying to learn more to do my job better. These values are not just important for my job - they are important to who I am.

I always knew I wanted to help people, but I was not sure how. During school, I saw many friends run away from their problems or try to fix them in ways that were not good. This made me want to study how people think and act. After finishing school in 2009, I took some time to think about what to do next.

That summer, something important happened. I met a young boy at my friend's house. He was there because his parents were hurting him. The next day, he called the police. I went to his home to try to help. I told the police about my school studies, and they asked me to talk to his parents. The parents tried to say their son was lying about the problems. This made me sure I wanted to become a social worker to help children with family problems.

I also believe everyone should be treated fairly. Our society says each person is special, but often pushes people to be the same as everyone else. I do not like this. In school, I showed who I really was: I made my hair different colors, dressed in my own way, and stood up for people who were treated badly because they were different. I fought against people being mean to others because of their skin color or who they loved. I will always stand up for what is right and fair for everyone.

This paper looks at two ways to understand sleep problems, especially when people cannot sleep well. One way looks at how the body and genes affect sleep. The other way studies how a person's life, culture, and living conditions affect their sleep.

When someone has trouble sleeping, doctors put it into one of three groups. The first group includes problems that come directly from sleep itself. The second group includes sleep problems that happen because of mental health issues. The third group includes sleep problems that come from health problems or medicine use.

The first group has two types of sleep problems. One type involves having trouble falling asleep or staying asleep. The other type makes it hard to stay awake during the day. Some people may also walk or have bad dreams while sleeping. These problems must last for at least one month to be seen as serious.

Scientists have found that special cells in the brain control when we sleep and when we are awake. They tested this idea using mice. They found that certain parts of brain cells help control sleep. When these parts work well, sleep is normal. When they do not work well, sleep problems can happen. If someone's family has these cell problems, they might also have trouble sleeping. This can make it hard to do well in school or work, or even simple daily tasks.

This understanding helps doctors know why some people have trouble sleeping. It also shows how sleep problems can run in families and affect daily life.

I have been a student at University Park for more than two years now. Moving around this large school area is hard for many students, including me. When I first came here, I lived in East Halls, which is very far from the center of school. Walking from my room to my classes near the middle of school could take 25 minutes, especially when the weather was bad.

I learned from an older student that not long ago, East Halls was far from other buildings, with much empty land between them. Now that empty land has new sports fields and big buildings. As our school grows bigger, it becomes harder to get from place to place. The best answer to this problem is the bicycle. But just having bikes is not enough. Students need to use them, and the school needs to make it easier for people to ride bikes.

A friend who started riding his bike again after many years told me he was sorry he ever stopped. He said bikes are the best way to move around school. Riding a bike is good for your health and uses very little energy. A simple breakfast can give you power to ride many miles.

I now live away from school, but my home is as far from classes as some school rooms are. Buying a bike was the best thing I did this year. I have class in Thomas building every day, which would take 25 minutes to reach by walking. On my bike, I can get there in 5 minutes if I ride fast. The only problem is that the shortest way there, Pollock Road, can be hard to travel on.

Walking is fine, but I do not have enough time for it. Without my bike, I would have to walk everywhere. Walking to Thomas building every day would take 40 more minutes than riding. That means more than two hours every week just for one class. When you think about going to other classes and meetings, it takes too much time to walk.

In his book "Brave New World," writer Aldous Huxley warns us about problems with technology and money-driven systems. He creates a future world where people are made to think the same way. In this world, everyone must seek quick happiness and put the group before themselves.

The people in this story are controlled by leaders who tell them what to think. When we look at the book through the ideas of Karl Marx, we see Huxley was worried about how society was changing. Marx's ideas about people being made the same and losing their individual worth help us understand the book's message about problems in the growing money system of Huxley's time.

The book shows how people are kept from knowing the truth about their place in society. The lower groups of people are made to want things they don't need. They learn this through sleep-teaching, which makes them want to buy and use more things. The top leaders use this to control them. The lower groups don't know they are being controlled, and most of the upper groups who do know don't try to change things.

In this future world, real friendships between different kinds of people don't exist. Even the main people in the story are not fully developed as real persons. This might show how Huxley thought technology and money systems were taking away people's ability to think freely. There is no love in this world. Men only talk about how women look, and women freely talk about their physical relationships without feeling shame. Each group of people accepts their place in society without question. They follow orders and stay in line, thinking they are better off if they keep buying things and doing what they are told.

I took a class about Islam at my school four years ago. In class, we often talked about whether Islam teaches peace or not. This question is even more important today. Since the September 11 attacks, I have seen how news groups changed their views. At first, they were against Islam. Now, they are very accepting of Islam in America. In 2001, no one would have thought we could have someone like Barack Obama, who has family members who were Muslim, run for president.

The story of Muhammad's life interests me because what I read seems different from what I learned before. I had learned that Muhammad made people follow Islam by force when he took control of their lands. But the book shows him as a good man who was not understood by others. It says people came to him on their own to learn his teachings.

I saw that the book tells stories about Muhammad that are very much like stories about Jesus. For example, it tells how Muhammad made a small amount of food become enough to feed forty men. I think the writers wanted to make Muhammad seem like a quiet, good man who did special things. This bothers me because it makes Jesus' life and special works seem less important. It feels like they are taking Jesus' story and saying it was Muhammad's story.

The book has many stories about people becoming Muslim by their own choice. But these stories come from people who heard it from others, who heard it from others. This makes me doubt if the stories are true.

What bothers me most is how the book shows Muhammad as a good, quiet, and wise man. But what we know about the past shows he was not always gentle and quiet. I wonder if Muslims today know the true story of how Muhammad gained power.

The ideas Jesus taught during his life were quickly changed as Christian thinking grew after his death. Looking at history, we see Christianity moving further from what Jesus first taught. Today, more people seem to understand this and want change. While some people still hold firmly to old ways of thinking, they may not be enough to stop new ideas. Christians will learn more about their history in the years ahead. Many will want to separate later church teachings from what Jesus actually meant. This change may take many years, but it will happen.

There will be a big turn in how Christianity moves forward. It will go back toward its first form. People will remove added teachings one by one, like going back in time. In the end, only Jesus' original message from God will remain. When this happens across America and Europe, many people will follow only Jesus' ideas, as if living in his time. Churches will still be important leaders. But as people go back to earlier beliefs, the many different kinds of Christianity will become more alike. Instead of having many different ways of worship, churches will become more similar.

History shows us that big changes can happen. For example, Romans once killed Christians, but later Rome became Christian. Our country once had slaves, but now has African-American leaders. Christianity will go through this kind of change, looking for its roots. This will happen partly because people will start to understand Jesus' words as having deeper meaning, not just taking them word for word.

Looking back in time, we find Judaism, where Christianity began. By the time Rome took control of Jerusalem in 63 BCE, Jewish people believed in one God, followed their holy books, and thought God had given them their religion. But Jewish people were not all the same. They were split into different groups: the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and most people who were not in any special group.

I think The Jungle shows that people naturally want things for themselves. They care most about making their own lives better and rarely help those who have less. The book shows this in several ways, especially through the factory owners and managers.

These business leaders only want to make their companies bigger and richer. They do not worry about who gets hurt when they try to grow their business. In the book, Upton Sinclair describes the factories with "smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This shows how the owners do not care about the damage their factories cause. They ignore the dark smoke from their buildings and the animal waste that runs into the streets from their meat-processing areas.

The owners also treat their workers badly. They will do anything to save or make more money. As the book says, "a man counted for nothing against a dollar." They make people work long hours in dangerous places. They can fire many workers at once without warning or help. During this time, there were few laws to protect workers. This meant owners could force people to work faster and in unsafe conditions.

The workers had no choice but to live with these terrible conditions both at work and at home. There were no groups to help them or give them information about their rights. Some worker groups existed but often took money from the poor workers instead of helping them. The workers were treated so badly that the book compares them to slaves. They were poor people, mostly from other countries, who could barely feed their families. They had to depend on cruel business owners who treated them as badly as slave owners once did.

Edgar Allan Poe wrote a poem called "Dream-land" which he thought was one of his better works. In this poem, he uses the word "Thule" two times. This word comes from old stories about a far-away island north of Britain. While the word appeared in very old writing by Virgil, Poe likely knew it from more recent German writing.

Poe read many German writers. One important German writer was Goethe, who wrote a famous story called "Faust." Inside "Faust," there is a smaller poem about "The King of Thule." This poem tells of a sad king whose wife died after giving him a special cup. The king drinks too much and cries for his dead wife. Finally, he gives away everything except the cup. He then walks to a high place above the sea, throws the cup into the water, and dies.

The king in Goethe's poem is much like the person in Poe's "Dream-land." Both stories show dark, lonely places and sad people who have lost loved ones. Poe used the word "Thule" in another story called "The Pit and the Pendulum" around the same time.

We know Poe knew about Goethe's work because Poe respected other writers who admired Goethe. Also, many people were making new versions of Goethe's works when Poe was writing. The way Poe writes about Thule in "Dream-land" shows he probably read Goethe's poem about the King of Thule. His poem seems to take us into the same dark, sad world that Goethe created.

Can a store be made to pay extra money as punishment in California if a customer gets hurt from falling on spilled food? Here is what happened:

A woman named Jennifer Palmer fell in a store called D&D Markets. She slipped on applesauce that was spilled on the floor. Before she fell, two workers told the store manager about the spill. The manager, Paul Martin, did not clean it up because he was eating his dinner. He waited thirty minutes, and during that time, Palmer fell and hurt her back badly.

The law in California says stores must pay extra money as punishment if they do very bad things on purpose or if they know something is dangerous but do not fix it. Palmer can ask for this extra money because:

1. The manager knew about the spill but did nothing
2. Six other people had fallen in the store that same year
3. The manager chose to eat instead of keeping customers safe

The facts show the manager knew the spill could hurt someone. He had seen other people get hurt from falls before. Still, he did nothing when told about the spill two times. Because of this, a judge will likely let Palmer ask for extra money as punishment.

The law calls this kind of payment "punitive damages." To get this money, Palmer must show the manager acted very badly by knowing about the danger but choosing to ignore it. Based on what happened, she has a good chance of proving this.

She always felt she needed something. This feeling would not go away. It began when she was fourteen, as she entered her teenage years. Now at seventeen, the feeling remained. She knew she wanted a person, not a thing. Yet no boys interested her. Some boys liked her and tried to get her attention, but she felt nothing for them. She often asked herself why she was different from other teenage girls. After thinking about this for years, she had ideas but no clear answers. So she continued to live, wondering about her feelings.

Life at home was usually quiet. Her parents were good people who lived peacefully. They rarely fought with each other or with her. The only problems came when she tried to show she could make her own choices. Her parents were calm, but she was full of life and fun. People liked her because she was both friendly and kind.

But this day was not quiet. As she walked around the house looking for something to do, she heard her mother cry out from the kitchen. She ran to the kitchen, worried, and called out, "Mom? Mom, what's wrong?" She found her mother on the floor, clearly hurting. Her mother kept saying "ow" while trying to breathe. The daughter knelt beside her mother to help. "Please... take me to... the hospital," her mother said with difficulty. "Show me where to hold you," the daughter said. She was glad she had learned how to lift heavy things. She carried her mother to the car, placed her carefully in the back seat, and drove away.

The hospital always smelled clean but scary. The daughter did not notice this because she could only think about helping her mother. She carried her mother inside and called for help. Doctors came quickly. They put her mother on a wheeled bed and took her away to check her. The daughter had to wait and worry alone.

Later, she learned her mother had fallen from a small ladder while trying to reach a flower pot from the highest shelf.

This study looked at how eating a Mediterranean-style diet might help prevent heart disease and stroke. The Mediterranean diet includes lots of plant foods, like fruits, nuts, grains, and beans. It also includes fish and healthy oils, but less meat and animal fat. People who follow this diet may drink small amounts of wine.

Earlier studies showed that people who ate this way had better heart health and lived longer. One study found that this diet worked better than a low-fat diet for losing weight and improving blood test results in overweight people.

The researchers studied 74,886 women who were nurses. These women were between 38 and 63 years old and were healthy when the study began. Over 20 years, from 1984 to 2004, the nurses filled out forms six times about what they ate. Almost all the nurses stayed in the study for the full time.

The researchers checked hospital records and death certificates to confirm when nurses had heart attacks or strokes. They also looked at other health factors like weight, smoking, exercise, and medicine use.

To get the best picture of how the women ate over time, the researchers averaged their diet scores from different years. They were careful to consider other things that might affect health, like age and exercise.

After studying the results for 20 years, they found 2,391 cases of heart disease and 1,763 strokes. Women who followed the Mediterranean diet most closely had much less risk of both heart disease and stroke compared to those who did not follow the diet. The risk was about 29 percent lower for those who ate the Mediterranean way.

A young actress stands on a street with a sign. The sign suggests that a cruel leader lives in Burma. 

Burma, also called Myanmar, is a country in Asia. Since 1962, military leaders have controlled the country with force. In 2007, people went to the streets to protest against these leaders. Many of the protesters were religious men wearing orange clothes. These protests became known as the Orange Movement.

As more people joined the protests, the military leaders became angry. They attacked religious buildings and hurt many people. They also stopped news reporters from other countries from showing what was happening. One photographer from Japan was killed just for taking pictures. The government said only thirteen people died, but a military officer who left his job said thousands were killed.

This kind of cruel control has happened many times in history. Leaders often try to stop people who disagree with them. In 1989, many students and workers gathered in China's main square to ask for more freedom. The Chinese government's soldiers killed hundreds or maybe thousands of people. In the 1990s, one group in Rwanda killed many people from another group. And during World War Two, Hitler and his followers killed millions of Jewish people.

Governments that want complete control often hurt their own people. They try to stop anyone who speaks against them. This has happened throughout history, and it still happens today.

Duke Ellington was very important to jazz music. He led his band for many years and knew how to write music that made each player sound their best. While he played piano, his greatest skill was writing music that brought out special qualities in his band members.

Ellington created music that let players make up their own parts while also writing exact notes for others to play. He understood how each person in his band played and wrote music that showed their special skills. He also knew how to make the whole band sound good together. Because of this, he wrote some of the best jazz music ever made.

The Grove Music book talks about how Ellington used the human voice as another instrument in his music. We can hear this in his song "Creole Love Call." This song shows how he could write music that made both singers and players sound good together. The song has six main parts:

Part 1: Voice and wind instruments play back and forth
Part 2: Quiet trumpet plays alone
Part 3: High clarinet plays alone with soft piano
Part 4: Whole band plays together
Part 5: Wind instruments lead, with other instruments adding beat
Part 6: Voice and winds play together again, with voice making special sounds

The song ends with a short singing part and an unusual note from the trombone.

In other songs like "Hot and Bothered," Ellington showed how well he could write for both singers and players. He had trumpet player "Bubber" Miley play with singer Baby Cox in a way that made their sounds work well together. In "It Don't Mean a Thing," he used Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's special way of playing trombone to start the song. These songs show how Ellington could bring different sounds together to make great music.

How do living things change over time? What limits the way they can change? In 1917, a scientist named D'Arcy Thompson said we did not know how to use numbers to describe even the simplest living things. This is still true today.

Recently, scientists have used numbers to study how sea shells grow and change over time. Our study looks at a type of sea animal called Prunum. We want to understand how these shells grow and change. We took X-ray pictures of different Prunum shells to measure important parts. We put these numbers into a computer program called CerioShell. This helped us see what kinds of shell shapes are possible for Prunum. We are also watching how living Prunum grow to better understand how they change over long periods.

A shell is like a tube that goes around in a circle many times. Each circle is called a whorl. The whorls wrap around the middle of the shell, which is called the columella. The line between each whorl is called a suture. The biggest whorl is usually the last one, called the body whorl. All other whorls make up the spire. The top of the spire is called the apex, and the bottom is called the base. The animal comes out through a hole called the aperture.

You can look at shells from different sides: the top, bottom, front (where you can see the opening), and back. Usually, people look at shells from the front, with the top pointing up.

To count whorls, look at the shell from the top. Find where the first line (suture) starts. Draw a line to split the shell in two parts. Count the whorls from this line. You can count parts of whorls by quarters (like one and a quarter whorls).

As the animal builds its shell, it makes new openings that form a path. Scientists can measure this path by looking at the center of each opening and how wide and tall it is.

We can draw this path and write it as numbers. When we have these numbers, we can change them to see how different shells might look.

In Indonesia, the number of babies and young children who die has stayed about the same for the past ten years. The country has made progress in providing clean water and better living conditions. However, the health of mothers and children is not improving fast enough to reach important goals set for 2015.

More births now happen with trained health workers present, about 72 out of 100. But many of these workers are traditional helpers who cannot deal with serious problems during birth. This means many mothers still die from losing too much blood. Also, fewer sick children under five years old are seeing doctors for stomach problems. Not enough mothers get care after having their babies.

Only 4 out of 100 mothers have their babies by operation when needed. In cities, 7 out of 100 mothers get these operations, but in rural areas, only 2 out of 100 do. This shows that health care is much better in cities than in rural areas. Poor people also have much more trouble getting health care than rich people, probably because they cannot pay for it.

Indonesia must decide how to fix these problems. They could make special programs just for mothers and babies, or they could try to make the whole health system better. Special programs might show quick results and be easier to manage. But these programs can cause problems too. When a lot of money goes to one health program, other important health needs may be forgotten. Also, having many different programs working separately can waste time and money.

Over the past hundred years, popular music has grown to include many different kinds. Today, there are so many kinds of music that it is hard to list them all. Each kind of music, like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, has created many smaller groups within itself.

Heavy Metal rock music has become one of the most interesting kinds of popular music in the past forty years. It shows many different feelings, often dark ones. Soon after Heavy Metal began, people found they could change it in many ways. They made new kinds of Heavy Metal, and then made even more kinds from those. This continues today.

Now there are so many different kinds of Heavy Metal that it is hard to say exactly what it is. It has taken ideas from many other kinds of music. To understand Heavy Metal today, we need to know how it started and why it became more than just another kind of music.

Heavy Metal is often about dark things. It uses more of everything - more loud sounds, more angry feelings, and more show. The people who play Heavy Metal must be very good at playing their instruments. In the middle of the 1970s, many people used drugs, which led to strange and different music. Heavy Metal was different from other popular music because it showed the darker side of feelings. Some of these dark ideas came from old music of the Romantic time.

The song "Helter Skelter" by the Beatles shows how Heavy Metal began. The Beatles wrote this song to show they could make music as strong as the Rolling Stones. They put this darker, stronger song on their White Album. Some people think this was one of the first Heavy Metal songs.

Many years before artists began making strange dream-like pictures, Henri Rousseau was already painting his own dreams. His famous painting from 1910, called "The Dream," shows a woman looking with wonder at the land she sees in her sleep. The painting also shows what Rousseau himself wanted most - to be accepted and praised by other artists. From the start of his work, he wanted people to like his art, but this was not easy to achieve.

Rousseau was born in 1844 in a small French town called Laval. His father sold metal goods and lived well. Rousseau never went to art school. Instead, he worked for the government collecting money from people at city gates until he was forty years old. His life was full of sadness. His first wife died, and he lost eight babies. Only one child, his daughter Julia, lived. To feel better, he turned to painting.

Unlike other artists of his time who painted pictures of poor people in a pretty way, Rousseau painted like a simple person because that is what he was. He wanted very much to be accepted by other artists. This was hard because he started painting late in life and had no training. He was working at the same time as many well-known artists like Matisse. While Matisse tried to paint in new and different ways, Rousseau just wanted to paint pictures that would make other artists accept him.

Many wise people have seen a close link between what is good and what is beautiful. I believe there is a deep reason for this connection. The poet John Keats wrote that "Beauty is truth, truth beauty." He said this is all we need to know.

We learn many things through school and life experience. But we seem to understand beauty and goodness in a different way. When we study art and good behavior, we try to explain why something is beautiful or right, rather than make rules about it.

When we talk about art or good actions, we can never fully explain why they move us. Take the famous painting Mona Lisa by Leonardo da Vinci. We can talk about how it is painted or what it meant in its time. But these words do not fully tell us why it is great art. Often, when people talk about art they love, they first say, "There is just something about it." I think both art and good behavior have qualities we cannot completely describe.

The writer Flannery O'Connor once said that we tell stories because simple statements are not enough. No matter how well we describe a book or painting, something special remains beyond our words. The same is true for good behavior and right actions.

I believe art and good behavior are closely connected because we feel them deeply in our hearts. They touch us in ways we cannot fully explain. This is especially true with books and stories. Stories show us what is right and wrong, just as life does. We care about stories because they help us understand these important ideas about how to live.

Germany today is a strong and united nation. Its culture spreads from the mountains in the south to the northern seas. You can feel this same culture as you travel from the western city of Cologne to the eastern city of Dresden. Germany's culture comes from many different groups of people who lived there long ago.

The old name for Germany was Germania. No one knows exactly where this name came from. A Roman writer named Tacitus said the name came from a group called the Tungrians. Julius Caesar was the first to write the word "Germanus" when he wrote about his wars. He learned this name from people called the Gauls. Some think the name came from the word for the fighting stick they used, while others say it came from a word meaning "to shout."

Tacitus wrote in the year 98 that the German people were the first to live in these lands. He thought they did not mix with other groups. He asked why anyone would want to leave warm lands to live in Germania with its cold weather and dark forests.

The Romans did not want to live in Germania. They went there to get goods and sometimes to fight, but they usually went back home. The German people lived near the edge of the Roman lands. They sold things to the Romans and some joined the Roman army.

The play Twelfth Night teaches us about hiding who we really are. While pretending to be someone else can help us for a time, we must eventually return to our true selves. If we do not, we might lose who we really are. However, when we stop pretending, some people might feel hurt or angry because we tricked them.

The story looks closely at what happens when someone pretends to be the opposite sex. This brings up an important question: why would someone do this? In the play, Viola does it to stay safe. She says she needs help to dress like a man so she can work for a noble person. She is in a new place and fears for her safety.

Viola's plan works to keep her safe, but it causes problems. Women do not become her friends because they think she is a man. Also, a woman named Olivia falls in love with her, thinking she is a man named Cesario. At the same time, Viola has feelings for Orsino but cannot show them because he thinks she is a man.

For today's readers, the play shows how pretending to be someone else can bring hidden feelings into the open. Both Olivia and Orsino act differently because of Viola's disguise. Some might wonder if Olivia falls in love with Cesario because she really likes women. But this is probably not what Shakespeare meant. Instead, he might be making fun of people who only care about how others look.

We can see this when Olivia quickly changes her love from Cesario to Sebastian, Viola's twin brother. In the end, Olivia accepts Viola as family instead of a love interest, calling her "sister."

The German control of other lands in Africa was often very cruel. This was especially true in South West Africa, where they killed many local Ovaherero and Nama people. However, German rule was different in each area they controlled. The way they taught people was also different from place to place.

When the British took control of German East Africa in 1919, they found many African people who could read and write well. Other writers at the time also said good things about German teaching in Kamerun and other areas. 

The situation in South West Africa (now called Namibia) was very different. In East Africa, the government made schools and helped teach local people. But in South West Africa, they left the teaching of local people to church groups, giving them little help. The government did spend much money to teach European people living there. They built schools for Europeans and gave more help to church schools for Europeans.

These choices about schools had long-lasting effects on South West Africa. While other German-controlled areas had many African people who could read and write, most people in South West Africa could not read or write at all. Many things caused this difference, including how people thought and acted, how the government worked, and how money was used.

South West Africa was different from other German-controlled areas because it had better weather, even though much of the land was dry. Because of this, more European people lived there. By 1913, almost 15,000 white people lived in South West Africa. The next highest number was in East Africa, with only 5,336 white people.

Many people have written about schools in German-controlled areas. Most early writing was in German and just told how the schools worked. Later, English writers compared schools in different areas. They showed how teaching was different in each place. One important writer, Cohen, looked at why schools in South West Africa and East Africa were so different. Cohen said that having many European people living in South West Africa made the schools there very different.

The United States and Mexico were not friendly nations for many years, from 1836 to 1893. The worst time in their relationship was during the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848. In this war, the United States fought Mexico and won. As a result, the United States took control of Texas and other land in the southwest.

The two countries had many differences that caused problems. They had different religions and ways of life. They also wanted the same things, which led to fights. This is common for countries that share a border. Mexico and Cuba are the only countries in the Americas that have had long-lasting problems with the United States.

Religion was a big reason for the bad feelings between the United States and Mexico. In the 1800s, Americans did not like Catholic churches or kings. Mexico was Catholic, just like Spain, the country that once controlled it. The United States was more like England, which was not Catholic. These old feelings made it hard for the two countries to be friends.

During the 57 years of poor relations, the United States and Mexico had 17 different fights. Most of these fights were about the border between the two countries. Bad people would cross the border to cause trouble. Both countries had to use their armies to stop these problems.

The fighting began to stop when Mexico started to need help from the United States. Also, the United States stopped trying to take more land. Instead, it wanted to do business with Mexico. This helped the two countries become more friendly by the end of the 1800s.

I became sick fifteen years ago. The illness came quickly and without warning. I had never heard of it before.

I was working as a nurse then. I chose nursing because I wanted to feel safe and secure, something I did not have when I was young. People told me, "You will always find work because people will always get sick." Even though I wanted to be a scientist or writer, I became a nurse instead.

Then, at age 46, I was alone and had very little money. I could not work anymore. Today, I still cannot work. After fifteen years of getting help from the government, I own almost nothing. I live day by day, but it is hard. I do not feel safe or good about myself. Nothing is sure in my life now. But I know one truth: I could not have lived through these years without help from my family and friends. When bad things happen, you do not feel strong at all.

Life will always have problems, big and small. You cannot be ready for everything. Some problems are too big to face alone.

I agree that in America, we should not depend only on the government. It is not working well. But I would rather see Americans helping each other again, instead of trying to live alone and apart.

Some people talk about how Americans should be strong alone. But what really helped our early settlers was working together and sharing. The people who crossed the mountains in wagons did not make it by being alone.

It is good to be ready for problems. I have emergency supplies: medical things, water cleaning tablets, and tape for windows. I have lights, batteries, matches, and food in cans. If you have land and can grow and save food, that is good. Having a wood stove is also good if you do not live in an apartment.

But while you get ready, it is important to know the people who live near you.

Around 2,500 years ago, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. During his life, he left his wealth behind and found deep wisdom. His teachings created Buddhism, and the oldest form is called Theravada Buddhism.

The religion has changed much since Buddha's time. In Sri Lanka, where many follow Theravada Buddhism, people take part in a yearly water ceremony. Both religious teachers and regular people join this event. While Buddha never spoke about such celebrations, they have become part of the religion. Changes can be seen in both small traditions and the deep teachings about finding peace.

The Buddhist community has had to change its basic ideas over time. These changes came from both Buddhist and non-Buddhist sources. Some changes helped the religion grow, while others tried to harm it.

To understand these changes better, we need to know a few important things. Changes from inside Buddhism came from its own people. Changes from outside came from others. Some forces tried to hurt Buddhism because they did not like it. Other forces did not mean to help or hurt Buddhism, but still affected it.

At its heart, Buddhism has some main ideas. Buddhists follow three important things: Buddha, his teachings, and the community of Buddhist teachers. The teachings are written in three main books. These books tell people how to live, what rules to follow, and how to think about life.

Buddhism teaches that life includes suffering, that nothing stays the same forever, and that people do not have a permanent soul. People keep being born again and again until they find wisdom. To find peace, people must stop wanting too much, being angry, and being confused.

Buddhist teachers must follow many rules. Regular people follow five main rules: do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not act badly in love matters, and do not use things that harm the mind. The most important teaching is that life includes suffering, suffering comes from wanting things too much, and there is a way to end suffering.

original_texts:
Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a security that is designed to track an index, a commodity or a basket of assets like an index fund, but is more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange.  An ETF gives you the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of single stock ownership like the ability to sell short, buy on margin and purchase as few as a one share in any transaction.  Though these benefits are extremely attractive, the expense ratios of ETFs are far lower than those of the average mutual fund.  Unfortunately, there are some down sides, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just as you would pay on a stock order.  Another benefit of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available.  Though these benefits are clearly stated, it is always a good exercise for the savvy financial investor to evaluate whether stated benefits, like diversification, do indeed exist, and the extent to which they exist.  For the purposes of this effort, we will be examining the ETF IHF and comparing it against the top 10 holdings that comprise the ETF to determine whether the benefits of a owning a single ETF come close to the benefits of owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks and also whether or not there are better configurations of the same stocks that would provide a more optimal sharp ratio or return.
	In order to evaluate the ETF, it would become rather unwieldy to include every holding, therefore we have decided to include only the top ten holdings accounting for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF.  Below are the top 10 holdings and the percentage of total assets.

	In order to gain an estimation of how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current % of assets, normalized to 100%, to  calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolioâ€™s Beta and Return if the portfolio was made up entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion that the ETF has established through their holdings.  The calculations of Beta and return are included in the below chart.

From the above chart it is evident that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns.  It is also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is .12 lower than the ETF as a whole.  From the results completed thus far, it seems that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower beta.  However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.
	In order to evaluate whether or not these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% in order to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a precipitous drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. That was a bit disheartening, and it is hard to say why that might have happened. With the onset of winter at a New England campus, there is clearly a drop in people commuting either by bicycle or by foot, which may account for some portion of the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester when everyone is very busy finishing schoolwork, processing grades, and so forth. Filling out the commuter log might just have slipped off the radar screen for many folks. In addition, December brings the onset of the busy holiday season and the resulting month-long break for students and faculty, during which time many do not even need to come to campus at all. Classes then resume for the spring semester in late January, perhaps also a clue to the low number of logs for that month. But none of that really explains the low number of submissions for February. One might also conjecture that any project of this type is going to have an initial burst of energy and excitement at the outset, which might then naturally decline. In an effort to combat this trend, we created the Carpool Challenge Week, a special blitz campaign in March to try and reinvigorate the initiative, which did result in an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we experienced was how to maintain project momentum in the face of both a natural decrease in engagement, but also specifically the problem of holiday and semester breaks experienced in higher education. 
Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars. This is deeply embedded in our culture. Therefore, it is essential to provide incentives for engaging in alternative modes of commuting. We gave out a lot prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see, however, how some even larger prizes might have affected participation – such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could have also helped to combat that dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes didn’t really change during the course of the project. If the prizes, however, were to increase in value over the course of the project, that might have helped. The gift cards seemed to be more than adequate at the outset of the project, but if we had announced in December the addition of a couple of bicycles, and then in January the addition of a hybrid or electric car, one can only think that participating and engagement would have increased instead of decreasing.

In looking through the Library of Congress’s library of early Edison films, I decided to view all of the trick films, of which there were fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films generally take advantage of creative editing to produce illusions. My film study generally focused on describing the poetics for the majority of trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier characteristics present in a few of the later films. Largely, the trick film at the turn of the century is set-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, features no camera movement, uses long and medium shots, and adheres to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, there are some films at the beginning of the twentieth century that dare to break these guidelines by introducing aspects such as multiple shots.
One of the most noticeable aspects that the trick films share in common is their filming in an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films, and drew its root from the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One of the limitations inherent in the use of the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side, and do not walk towards or away from the camera. Take, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they go out of the frame, the camera does not follow them.
The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This borrows from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the borders of the stage. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.
Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative usage of the trick films; most of them focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. Note, however, that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer’s eyes does not actually equal one physical shot.
